items.name: James O'Neill
items.overview: James O'Neill spent the first 10 years of this century working for Microsoft where he discovered PowerShell, and has been talking about it to anyone who will listen ever since. He now works freelance and for the last year has been using PowerShell and DSC to automate processes for one of Britiain's best known manufacturing companies. Over a longer period he has been a major contributor to the importExcel module on the PowerShell gallery, and this module has been used to deliver management information about that DSC has configured and other aspects of system state. He lives near Oxford, England and has developed the annoying habit of writing about himself in the third person.

items.name: Christoph Bergmeister
items.overview: I am a developer by day with a focus on DevOps, automation and CI/CD. By night I contribute to the open source PowerShell repos and I am also appointed as a maintainer of [PSScriptAnalyzer](https://github.com/PowerShell/PSScriptAnalyzer).

items.name: Walter Legowski
items.overview:
###**Walter Legowski - @SadProcessor**
Windows Security Consultant by day,
DIY Offensive PowerShell Tool Smith by night.
I like Lego, Tools, (Offensive) PowerShell and some other things.
My Colleagues tell me I say 'PowerShell' way too often... Can't help it.
Love the PowerShell Community and am trying to give back a bit of what it gave me…

items.name: Paul DeArment Jr
items.overview:
Name: Paul DeArment Jr
I am a member of the Systems Engineering team for Advocate Aurora Healthcare tasked with automating various platforms and projects. Before working for Advocate Aurora Healthcare, I worked for a company providing hosting for nursing homes across the United States and was tasked with developing a full fledged IAM application which integrated with ServiceNow, automation of VMWare builds, and supported the other IT teams within the company with automation of their tasks as well as troubleshooting issues they ran into.
All opinions and information shared is my opinion. Advocate Aurora Healthcare is not associated with any information I talk about, and no comments shared should be taken as endorsement from Advocate Aurora Healthcare.

items.name: Daniel Bohannon
items.overview:
Daniel Bohannon (@danielhbohannon) is a Senior Applied Security Researcher with FireEye’s Advanced Practices Team with over eight years of operations, security and Incident Response consulting experience.
He is the author of the Invoke-Obfuscation, Invoke-CradleCrafter and Invoke-DOSfuscation obfuscation frameworks and co-author of the Revoke-Obfuscation detection framework. He has presented at numerous conferences including Black Hat USA, DEF CON, BlueHat and DerbyCon.
Mr. Bohannon received a Master of Science in Information Security from the Georgia Institute of Technology (2013) and a Bachelor of Science in Computer Science from The University of Georgia (2010).
His primary research areas include obfuscation, evasion and methodology-based detection techniques for endpoint and network applied at scale.

items.name: James Petty
items.overview:
Hey there, I’m James... I have a passion for automation and PowerShell. Here I will blog about lots of thing including but not limited to SCCM, JEA, General HowTo’s etc…
I am also the co-chair for the Chattanooga PowerShell User Group as well as server on the organizing committee for PowerShell on the River, a 2 day PowerShell conference hosted in Chattanooga TN.
I also server as the CFO for PowerShell.org/DevOps Collective, Inc., a 501(c)(3)
A volunteer role for a nonprofit working in the technology education space. Help manage a + annual budget that includes scholarship programs and a 400-attendee annual community event. The nonprofit is focused on PowerShell, automation, and DevOps, and also runs numerous free online resources including PowerShell.org

items.name: Matt Wrock
items.overview: I've been active in the Windows devops open source community for several years. In addition to contributing to several popular devops tools, I authored Boxstarter (now under Chocolatey management), wrote the initial mocking implementation for Pester, and the first open source implementation of the PowerShell Remoting Protocol on Ruby. I'm currently a Principle Software Engineer at Chef where I have been responsible for bringing Habitat application automation to Windows.

items.name: Michael Bender
items.overview: Michael is a teacher at heart and has a passion for helping people learn the skills necessary to ‘level-up’ their careers. As a Cloud Ops Advocate at Microsoft, he works with the Operations and IT Pro communities to ‘Skill Up’ on Azure, and advocates for these communities in Azure Engineering. Before coming to Microsoft, Michael taught Windows Networking, server virtualization, and PowerShell at Madison Area Technical College for 13 years, along with creating multiple courses on Pluralsight covering Windows Server and PowerShell. Along with teaching, he is passionate about the IT Operations community. For the last eight years, he’s led up a global user group called The Krewe. This group provides a worldwide network for the sharing of ideas and solutions for many in the Operations community. He is active on Twitter @MichaelBender and blogs at itsallgeek2mike.com.

items.name: Adam Driscoll
items.overview: Adam Driscoll is a Microsoft Cloud and Datacenter MVP, software architect for STEALTHbits Technologies, small software business owner and triathlete. He has years of hardcore PowerShell experience. His current project focus is PowerShell Universal Dashboard.

items.name: Chris Hunt
items.overview: Chris is a distinguished software operator with the good fortune to have worked in incredible organizations like Ticketmaster and Stack Overflow. He has an unhealthy affection for the meta and working on projects that invoke "Yo Dawg" memes like writing automated tests for a testing framework that's a DSL abstracting a DSL. In 2017, he put together a single-day, single-track nano-conference following the PowerShell Summit and works to advance the conversation of DevOps on Windows.

items.name: Anthony Nocentino
items.overview: Meet Anthony Nocentino, Enterprise Architect, Founder and President of Centino Systems, Pluralsight Author, Microsoft Data Platform MVP, Corporate Problem Solver, and a voracious student of the latest computer science technology. Anthony is only satisfied when he finds the right technology resolution for his client's business needs. Business today thrives on data – from the C-Suite to the information worker. Anthony specializes in all things related to data – database systems, virtualization, system and network design, and performance engineering. He designs solutions, deploys the technology, and provides expertise on business system performance, architecture, and security. Anthony has a Masters in Computer Science and is working towards a PhD focusing on high performance/low latency data access algorithms on solid state disks.

items.name: Ashley McGlone
items.overview: Ashley McGlone is a former Microsoft Premier Field Engineer and now a Technical Account Manager at Tanium. He has a familiar face (or goatee) in the PowerShell community as a blogger, tweeter, and speaker. You can find his content on YouTube, TechNet, and Microsoft Virtual Academy. While at Microsoft Ashley created and delivered PowerShell training to customers around the world. Now at Tanium he is leveraging PowerShell on a realtime endpoint platform. Previous attendees of his sessions have said that he is both "informative and entertaining". Ashley's goal is to help people grow PowerShell adoption and usage in their enterprise environments to overcome daily IT challenges.

items.name: Brandon Olin
items.overview: Brandon is a Cloud Architect at Columbia Sportswear focusing on the cloud, automation, configuration management, and monitoring. He spends much of his time exploring new technologies to drive the business forward and loves to apply ideas pioneered in the DevOps community to the traditional enterprise environment with the goal of solving real-world business problems. Brandon is active in the PowerShell community with a number of projects published to the PowerShell Gallery.

items.name: Adam Murray
items.overview:
I am a doer, an optimist, and a technologist. With 20 years of experience in corporate IT and one startup behind me, I’ve recently embarked on my second startup, Tikabu, which provides premium consulting services in secure DevOps. Focusing on clients with a predominantly Microsoft technology stack, we help our customers become more agile at delivering solutions to their customers.

I’ve been passionate about PowerShell since its beta days. I recognised the potential and flexibility it gave me compared with the tools I started out with in automation, such as Kix and VBScript. Today, I remain a staunch PowerShell devotee; I’ve presented on the scripting language at user groups and am a two-time winner of the Quest PowerPack Challenge. PowerShell has become an integral part of the solutions that I develop day to day.

Throughout my career, I’ve served in both technical and people-management positions across the financial sector. My electrical-engineering degree has provided a strong foundation for the analytical and troubleshooting talents necessary for a successful IT career, and my MBA and additional continuing education have given me a broader and more well-informed business outlook. My ongoing thirst for technical knowledge has led to a thorough understanding of technology at all levels. More than just a vocation, technology is my passion both in and out of the workplace.

items.name: Andrew Pearce
items.overview: Andrew is a senior Systems Development Engineer with Amazon Web Services. His efforts focus on the design and implementation of highly available solutions that integrate AWS and Windows using PowerShell. He strives towards further enhancing automation capabilities and building CI/CD pipelines for Windows platforms at AWS. Andrew moved to Seattle with his family in 2015, after spending almost nine years automating the network of a small Australian Government agency.

items.name: Chris Gardner
items.overview:
Chris is a DevOps and ALM consultant with over 4 years' experience working with PowerShell. He has recently been focusing on using DSC to configure Windows for a variety of purposes, particularly when provisioning dev/test environments in Azure.

I'm a regular participant on the PowerShell Slack channels and speak at various UK user groups, PSConfAsia and a number of other international events.

items.name: Dakota Clark
items.overview:
Automate the world!

My name is Dakota Clark, I'm an IT professional that has found my passion in code thanks to PowerShell.
If you have an IT problem there's a good chance I can help you solve it!

Platform agnostic I can work my way around Windows or a Linux distro.

Looking to expand further into the .NET world with C#.

If I'm not coding I'd like to be dirt biking!

items.name: Daniel Franciscus
items.overview: Dan Franciscus is a systems engineer specializing in PowerShell, Active Directory, VMware, Chocolatey and Puppet. Dan is also a freelance tech writer who has been published on Tom's IT Pro, Ipswitch, 4sysops, and Techtarget. You can reach Dan at his blog winsysblog.com.

items.name: Ebru Cucen
items.overview: A curios developer, trying to understand why we do and challenge the boundaries to find out how can we do it better. IT is the best place for me to learn, ask and challenge. Also, a vegan mum, dreaming the world will be better if each one of us do one thing good every day.

items.name: Friedrich Weinmann
items.overview:
On the job, Fred is a Premier Field Engineer for Security at Microsoft. As a naturally lazy person he keeps automating things with PowerShell ... only to find new things to automate. Again.

In his putatively 'spare' time he contributes to the dbatools project, maintains and extends the PSFramework PowerShell module, runs a PowerShell Usergroup, speaks at conferences and other usergroups, reads tons of books and mixes cocktails.

items.name: Glenn Sarti
items.overview:
I’m located in Perth (Western Australia) where I now work at Puppet as Senior Software Developer on the Windows team. From December 2015 my family and I made the big move to Portland (Oregon, United States), but moved back to Perth in late 2017.

I have spent well over a decade as a Windows Client and Infrastructure engineer, with a heavy focus on automation and infrastructure software development. I was also a co-organiser for the Perth DevOps meetup and Portland PowerShell User Group, and have spoken at the Perth Dot Net, Java and DevOps meetups.

I’m also a contributor to Neo4j, helping out with management of Neo4j on Windows, and a maintainer of the Puppet Visual Studio Code Extension.

items.name: Jaap Brasser
items.overview:
Jaap is a Cloud and Automation Engineer and CDM MVP with a big passion for scripting and automation. As an IT professional Jaap is part of several professional communities, speaks & organizes technical events and writes articles on a variety of subjects on his personal blog and other websites or magazines.

[Blog](https://www.jaapbrasser.com), [Twitter](twitter.com/jaap_brasser), [GitHub](github.com/jaapbrasser)

items.name: James Arruda
items.overview:
James Arruda
CICD Person as FMGlobal - (no official title yet, just joined the team)
Former High School Physics teacher - maybe I will do quick physics demonstration as well :-) 1-2min..
People should listen to me because I am just like them, doing and learning from mistakes as I go along.
My favorite member of Wrong Direction is NorthEast.

I did a complete career change back to technology and spent the last 9-10 years learning, and still am. Hopefully I can help someone in the same way many others have helped me.

items.name: James Pogran
items.overview: James Pogran is a senior software engineer at Puppet, focusing on making Windows automation even better with Puppet. He wrote a book called Learning PowerShell DSC, which is in its second edition. James co-authored the Puppet Visual Studio Code extension, and contributes to several OSS projects on GitHub. He has been working with computers in some form or fashion for over 15 years. His first job was systems administration for a large military installation, then he moved on to developing monitoring software and automating large scale Windows environments for a major managed services provider. He loves finding out how things work, taking them apart, and making them work faster.

items.name: Jeremy Murrah
items.overview: Jeremy Murrah is an old OPS guy from the dark ages of computing. He started automating NT 4.0 installations and hasn't looked back. Classically trained as an Active Directory Administrator and Windows Engineer, he is currently engrossed in all things Powershell and is eagerly awaiting the death of the GUI.

items.name: Joel “Jaykul” Bennett
items.overview:
I'm passionate about building the happy path (aka the pit of success), and about helping others find it!

I've been blogging about PowerShell and answering questions about it's happy path and unhappy pitfalls on Twitter, IRC, Slack, Discord and Stack Overflow for a dozen years. I'm currently a DevOps and Azure automation engineer at Questionmark, and I've been professionally a PowerShell scripter for 8 years, a developer for 20, and a PowerShell MVP for 10. Ask me about #IT

items.name: Kevin Marquette
items.overview: I am a Sr. DevOps Engineer for loanDepot, Microsoft MVP, 2018 PowerShell Hero, and SoCal PowerShell User Group Organizer.

items.name: Kirill Kravtsov
items.overview:
DBA for more than 10 years, Powershell enthusiast and major dbatools contributor. I'm also a huge fan of DevOps mentality and an active Jenkins user, which left me with no choice other than using and developing tools that automate most of the database management aspects.
In my free time I enjoy travelling, playing video games, heavy metal music and many more.

items.name: Kirk Munro
items.overview: Kirk Munro is the world's first self-proclaimed Poshoholic, and a 12-time PowerShell MVP. Since being bitten by the PowerShell (PoSh) bug in 2006, Kirk has spent an enormous amount of time using and helping others learn PowerShell and automation, in roles of developer, evangelist, trainer, architect, Product Manager, and Director. These days he works as Senior Software Developer at Learn on Demand Systems, where he continues helping others learn by building technologies that help them learn. Outside of work, Kirk continues returning to his software developer roots, learning mobile technologies like Xamarin and Ruby on Rails, and taking courses online whenever he can make the time to do so.

items.name: Luc Dekens
items.overview: Luc is a co-author of the PowerCLI Refefrence Guide Ed 1 & 2. In his community contributions on the VMware VMTN forum he tries to spread his love for automation and PowerShell. He is a regular speaker at several conferences. He is awarded the VMware vExpert and the MSFT MVP title several times over the years.

items.name: Mark Kraus
items.overview: Mark Kraus is a Senior Systems Engineer at LinkedIn specializing in hybrid cloud Infrastructure as Code. He is a Former Microsoft MVP, PowerShell Core Project Collaborator, a heavy contributor to the Web Cmdlets code for PowerShell core, and a [opensource author & contributor](https://github.com/markekraus) to many PowerShell projects. He is the author of [Get-PowerShellBlog](https://get-powershellblog.blogspot.com/), a regular in [/r/PowerShell](https://www.reddit.com/r/PowerShell/), and can often be found on the [PoshCode Slack](http://poshcode.org/).

items.name: Mathias Jessen
Michael T Lombardi
items.overview:
Mike Lombardi is a sysadmin-turned-documentarian and automation engineer whose primary goal is to be a force multiplier for organizations and communities by
documenting, mentoring, and working to continuously improve processes and tooling. He maintains and contributes to [several open source projects](https://michaeltlombardi.gitlab.io/projects), co-organizes the [St. Louis PowerShell User Group](https://meetup.com/STLPSUG), was a contributing author and editor for the [PSConfBook]()and is the sometimes host of the technical community chat show, [ChatterOps](https://chatterops.org).

items.name: Mike F. Robbins
items.overview: Mike F. Robbins is a Microsoft Cloud and Datacenter Management MVP for Windows PowerShell. He is the creator of The PowerShell Conference Book, author of PowerShell 101: The No-Nonsense Beginner’s Guide to PowerShell, co-author of Windows PowerShell TFM 4th Edition, and a contributing author of a chapter in the PowerShell Deep Dives book. Mike is also the leader and co-founder of the Mississippi PowerShell User Group. He blogs at mikefrobbins.com and can be found on twitter @mikefrobbins.

items.name: Mike Kanakos
items.overview:
I’m an IT pro located in the Research Triangle Park area of North Carolina. I've spent my career supporting all flavors of Window operating systems from Windows 95 til today. I am proud to call myself a seasoned Active Directory Pro and PowerShell fanatic as well as a sysadmin who loves to solve problems in interesting ways. I have benefited so much from content and solutions provided by others over the years that I feel I am obligated to now give back to others who might be searching the web for solutions to problems they are facing. In the last eight months, I have created a blog that sees a decent amount of traffic, became the co-leader of the RTP PS user group, had a number of articles professionally published online. The highlight of my career has been to have contributed a chapter to the PowerShell Conference Book.

I am proud to say that I have started to make a presence for myself in the industry and have had the opportunity to share ideas with an amazing group of admins who share the same passion as I do for PowerShell. Last but not least, I serve as a mentor and teacher of PowerShell for my colleagues at work. I am nervous as hell to submitting this talk, but I believe that I can do it and willing to accept the risks and take that chance to put myself out there. It's what I have been doing all of 2018 and it hasn't let me down yet and I don't expect this to be any different.

items.name: Steven Murawski
items.overview: Steven is a Cloud Ops Advocate at Microsoft. Steven leads the Ops Advocate team focused on DevOps, SRE, and Cloud Native scenarios with Azure (and is a founding member of the League of Extraordinary Cloud DevOps Advocates). Steven is an active member of the Chef and WinOps communities and a maintainer for several open source projects, including Chef, Habitat, and Test-Kitchen.

items.name: Susan E Campbell
items.overview:
Susan Campbell has been in the IT industry since 1998, when she set up a Windows NT network at her office, including stringing cat5 cable through the ceiling and punching down patch panels! She has worked with some flavor of Windows servers and operating systems ever since, and began using PowerShell six years ago, when she was asked to create 300+ user accounts - by hand. Fortunately, she had time to plan and get better acquainted with PowerShell, and created those 300 accounts in just a few minutes. Seeing the power of PowerShell, she incorporated more automation into her work environment, and has been scripting ever since!

Personally, she is a mom of three, wife of original WordPress developer @dougal, sister of Microsoft MVP @arcanecode (yes - an entire family of geeks), and an Auburn alum - War Eagle!

items.name: Tara Raj
items.overview: My name is Tara Raj and I am a Program Manager II at Microsoft. An entrepreneur at heart, I've worked to ship new and interesting products for developers while at Microsoft. I'm the PM lead for the Windows Subsystem for Linux and I'm excited about working on innovative technologies for developers. I previously worked on SQL Server on Linux where I shipped the first public build of Azure Data Studio for cross-platform database development and mssql-scripter, a command-line tool for database scripting. My passion for the command line and Linux manifested itself while on SQL Server and has translated to my work on the WSL team. Outside of the office, I perform at improv comedy shows around Seattle and participate in all things sports.

items.name: Thomas Rayner
items.overview: Thomas Rayner is a Senior Security Service Engineer with many years of experience in IT. He is a master technologist, specializing in DevOps, systems and process automation, public, private and hybrid cloud, and PowerShell. Thomas is a former 4x Microsoft MVP, Honorary Scripting Guy, an international speaker, best-selling author, and instructor covering a vast array of IT topics.

items.name: Tome Tanasovski
items.overview: Tome is an executive for a market-leading global financial services firm in New York City where he focuses on cloud automation, cloud native patterns, distributed computing, and analytic frameworks. He is the founder and co-leader of the New York City PowerShell User group, a blogger, and speaks regularly at conferences and user groups. In 2011 he became a co-founder of the NYC Techstravaganza, coauthored the Windows PowerShell Bible, and received the title of Honorary Scripting Guy from the Hey Scripting Guy! blog. Tome has also received the MVP award from Microsoft for the last eight years in Windows PowerShell.
